Event Handling & Processing â€” Minimal Integration
ğŸ”¹ Idea

Instead of running logic directly from menu input,
we trigger events like:

CREATE_ACCOUNT

LOGIN

DEPOSIT

WITHDRAW

TRANSFER

Then the Bank class acts as an Event Processor, validating + performing actions.

âœ”ï¸ Add Event Interface
interface BankEvent {
    void process(Bank bank);
}

âœ”ï¸ Sample Event Classes

(Each event carries data â†’ Bank executes them)

Create Account Event
class CreateAccountEvent implements BankEvent {
    private String name, password;

    public CreateAccountEvent(String name, String password) {
        this.name = name;
        this.password = password;
    }

    @Override
    public void process(Bank bank) {
        bank.createNewAccount(name, password);
    }
}

Deposit Event
class DepositEvent implements BankEvent {
    private int accId;
    private double amt;

    public DepositEvent(int accId, double amt) {
        this.accId = accId;
        this.amt = amt;
    }

    @Override
    public void process(Bank bank) {
        bank.depositAmount(accId, amt);
    }
}

âœ”ï¸ Modify Bank to Handle Events
public void handleEvent(BankEvent e) {
    e.process(this);  // call event, pass bank object
}

âœ”ï¸ Controller Dispatching (Menu)
Old style:
if(option == 1) bank.createNewAccount(...)

New (Event-driven):
case 1: {
  String name = inputString("Enter name: ");
  String pass = inputPassword("Enter password: ");
  handleEvent(new CreateAccountEvent(name, pass));
  break;
}

âœ”ï¸ Example Add Deposit Event
case 3: {
  int id = inputInt("Enter acc ID: ");
  double amt = inputDouble("Amount: ");
  handleEvent(new DepositEvent(id, amt));
  break;
}

ğŸ§  How It Works

User Action â†’ Creates Event

Event holds only the required input

Event.process(bank)

Calls safe bank operations

Handles validation + data updates

UI stays clean

No business logic in menu

Easy to extend
